SERVICE 1: WORKFLOW API SERVICE
Responsibility: Acts as the entry point
. Accepts dynamic workflow submissions (JSON) via REST, validates basic structure, persists workflow definitions and DAG edges to the DB, creates initial task_run entries (marked as PENDING), and publishes the workflow.started event
. Everything must run inside a single DB transaction
.
What It Must NOT Do: It does not schedule tasks, execute logic, handle retries, or consume Kafka events
.
🧠 SERVICE 2: ORCHESTRATOR SERVICE
Responsibility: The "brain" of the system
. It listens to workflow.started, validates the DAG for cycles, maintains the dependency graph, and publishes runnable tasks to task.ready
. When it consumes task.completed or task.failed, it updates the database, unlocks child tasks, and decides on retries or Dead Letter Queue (DLQ) routing
. It also detects timeouts for tasks stuck in RUNNING
.
What It Must NOT Do: It performs no heavy computation or shell command execution
.
⚙ SERVICE 3: WORKER SERVICE
Responsibility: The compute-heavy execution layer
. It consumes from task.ready, marks the task as RUNNING atomically, and executes real system commands (e.g., git clone, mvn clean install) using Java's ProcessBuilder
. After execution, it captures stdout/stderr, updates the database, commits the Kafka offset, and publishes task.completed or task.failed events
.
    